segments.text: I have a lot of respect for a lot of the Civil Liberties Union positions and the people that work with it.
Of course some of their positions I don't agree with at all.
I'm not concerned about the rights of Ku Klux Klan people.
I'm not concerned about the rights of Nazi Party people.
I'm not concerned about the rights of John Birch people.
But as a whole, I think the ACLU is a very good institution with a lot of good work.
I think a legal education really helps a person examine the relationships between things.

If you're not careful, you go to college and you get channeled into too narrow a focus, and you don't begin to understand the connections between economics, history, government, law, literature, engineering, business,
In fact, our society too much wants us to become so-called experts.
But then as you go along, I just read a business section paper the other day, they want more lawyers now because they're generalists, what they call generalists.
They do understand more of the interconnections between various problems.
It really taught me a lot, my legal education.
law professors, not that they taught me that much law, but they sure taught me a lot about how to analyze things and how to develop a good shit detector.
I mean, you find out there's always 42 sides to a story if somebody's glib enough and articulate enough and you can come up with some crazy theory that will support anything.
What else we got?
Here we go.
What was the concept of the split rail?
Maybe I just better wrap out as briefly as I can what the rail was, how it occurred, and what it was about.
And out of that, you might get the answer to that.
Because it never was written down, or it never, unfortunately, never was
well enough conceived and understood for it to hold together.
So it was different things to different people, I guess is what I'm trying to say.
The Split Rail Inn was a very famous and well-liked honky-tonk here in town.
It was started after the Second World War.
It so happens by a second cousin of mine who
I didn't know until years later, was gay.
And he started that bar and did a good job of decorating it.
It was a drive-in restaurant.
They sold hamburgers, fish, and all.
He was in the military area during the Second World War, and they put up bamboo.
They had a bamboo garden area.
And then they used parachutes from the Second World War that they draped over a frame, where finally they put picnic tables.
And people would come here and drink beer, and a lot of veterans.
He started that place.
He also started another place that was well known here in Austin for years, the New Orleans.
And then several years after that, he killed himself.
I don't think he ever worked out his sexuality and relationship with society.
Too bad he didn't live to now.
A lot of those problems are being worked out or much better addressed.
But the Split Rail Inn started out as a drive-in restaurant beer joint.
During the 60s, it more or less got converted to a music place.
Threadgill, the old man, used to have a little gas station out there.
We'd yodel like Jimmy Rogers.
You all familiar with Jimmy Rogers, who he is or was?
He was singing breakman blues, a lot of yodeling.
Threadgill sings like that, did.
Threadgill started singing out at the Split Rail Inn.
It became very popular.
He'd play once a week.
And they started having other groups.

The guy that was a bar owner of them was a typical American small business man, very greedy, and let's get it on, bring your money, and I'll get you drunk, and you be quite nice, and I won't hurt you.
And then he...
But it had kind of a loose atmosphere.
And socially, it played a pretty significant role during the late 60s and early 70s when I was talking about that clash between hippies and rednecks.
And there was a wide variety of people that came to the split rail.
And there was lots of tension there between the long hairs and the rednecks.
But that got worked out.
And without too many fistfights or physical brutalities, lots of verbal abuse.
But a lot of that got worked out.
And those people became friends.
began to do things together politically and socially and sexually.
And that was the kind of place it was.
It was very open-minded.
And you'd find state senators there and lobbyists, and you'd find YNOs, and bikers, and hippies, and goat ropers, and Marxists, and the whole schmear.
I mean, it was a very good place.
And it changed ownership several times.
And each time it became more focused as a music place.
A lot of good musicians played there when they first came to Austin.
The Bonds, I don't know if you know Stevie Bonds, those guys played there back when they were first starting out.
Of course, didn't vibrate.
Marshall Ball, who used to be Freda and the Fire Dogs, she used to play there.
And I could go on and on.
A bunch of groups used to.
When they first came to Austin, that's one of the places they played.
And of course, I'd been going there for years.
As I said, I used to drink heavily.
I wasn't active politically or with friends or lovers, and I was usually drinking at a bar, listening to music.
And at one point in my life, for about nine years,
I lived with and loved a woman named Bobbi Nelson, who's a very fine person, a lawyer, an activist, a revolutionary, and a heavy feminist organizer.
We're no longer together.
In fact, she's married now to another man.
But Bobbi and I were living together.
We had a big house out in the university area.
And we had a number of people that lived with us.
And they were all highly active, highly articulate, tense people.
At one point, I was without a job.
She wanted to quit practicing law, did quit practicing law finally after we got the split rail.
I went to work at the split rail.
I lost my job as a painter.
I painted apartments for a couple of years.
And I was out of a job, and I went out to see the guy who owned it.
He used to be one of the top dogs in state bureaucracy over here, and he got fed up.
said to hell with it and went and bought the split rail.
At any rate, he gave me a job.
I went to work there.
Jim Parrish was his name, and he's from a wealthy family.
I didn't know that at the time, but he's from a wealthy family down in Corpus.
Bobby knew that because Bobby originally came from Corpus and went to high school with Parrish.
Time passed.
He decided to close the rail down.
We...

We'd been talking for a number of years that we wanted to have a restaurant, a bar, a music place, a counterculture place where you could have art and media and people getting together and talking about their lives and what they wanted to do and what they didn't like and so forth.
And we never could find one.
Of course, you always got the problem of money in this society, and it's a heavy-duty problem unless you want to sell your soul and screw a lot of folks.
At any rate, finally, he closed it down and
We had a group of three or four.
I don't want to go into all this detail.
It would take too long and it's very painful.
There were three or four of us that had met for several weeks, probably six or seven weeks, talking about the concepts of the place and how it ought to be run.
We didn't have the split rail at that time.
We were talking generally.
There were three women.
from the university area activists.
I can't even remember how to block their names.
It's a hell of a thing to say.
Because we ended up in a fight out there, and they ended up contrary to my position and Bobby's position.
But they were very fine activists.
They had a lot of respect for them.
The split rail, we kept talking to Jim Parrish, the owner,
you know, we'd like to buy it or it's possible for us to open it up.
He didn't want to reopen it.
He was having some problems with the alcoholic beverage commission.
And eventually, he decided that, and he was leasing it from me, a person who owned the basic lease from the landowner, if you follow me on all this.
Eventually, Parrish said, y'all take the place.
He gave it to us, which was a hell of a thing to do.
It was worth probably on the normal business market, $25,000, $30,000.
It had eight years to go on the lease.
Part of the building was over 100 years old.
There used to be a stage crossing down there.
Of course, it got burned down.
Eventually, the bikers burned us down.

But he let us have the lease, and he said, and we were good friends by then, and of course he knew Bobby, but Jim and I were good friends, and he said, you know, if y'all make it three or four years from now, you can give me $5,000 or $10,000.
I said, okay, we'll do that.

But we had to enter into the lease agreement with the person who had the basic lease and follow all the regulations of the lease, and we had to borrow money, and most of that was done on Bobby's credit.
I didn't have any credit by this time, and I have credit now.
I lost all my credit cards and credit in 1964, about eight credit cards and about $25,000 down the tubes when I dropped out of the Liberal Democrat business.
So Bobby is the one who came up with most of the credit.
We had this group of people who wanted to do this thing.
Of course, we knew this was different than starting a new place.
This is a place with a lot of history, a lot of tradition.
has been there and is well known in serving a certain function.

We put together a group of people and we did it very quickly which in my view later turned out to have serious problems with it because people got into it with different ideas about what it was about and what was permitted and not permitted and who makes decisions and all that but it was run on the idea was that everybody participate that works there and that everybody makes the same and all decisions
be made by general discussion and general decision, a new left concept.
In other words, it wasn't to be done by following parliamentary procedures and strict votes.
Of course, there are conflicts between trying to run any kind of an operation like that and trying to do a day-to-day business.
I mean, there's natural tensions.
There's certain things that have to be done.
These are the things that eventually we've got to work out as far as our society goes, I think.
So I guess I was kind of a manager.
We had three or four or five of us, I forget how many, that all had access to the checkbook, signed checks, that kind of thing.
But if questions came up and needed a decision immediately, I made the decision, if there hadn't been already some policy or statement made concerning that thing.
We tried to, and we did for a long time, do a pretty fair job as far as the menus, the type of food, good vegetables, not canned stuff, not bad product, but well done.
We broadened the music variety.
Eventually, that was one of the tension spots about how much country music, how much of this, how much of that.
Which bands do you have?
How do you handle fights or potential fights?
How do you handle a lot of sexist, macho cursing activity?
We had pretty good policy about that.

I mean, none of that was, as far as our policy goes, was tolerating men fuck up, they're supposed to leave, which is one of the reasons it eventually got us crosswise with some of the backers who have
down the road burned us down after we had barred them from coming there.
So, I mean, the concept of the split rail was that it was to be owned and operated by that group of people who put it together.
After the big argument came down between me, to a large extent,
with Bobby, but me to a large extent on one hand, and a good many of the staff who had worked at the Sprint Rail before were not from the university activist area.
And some of the activists, that was
the group that kind of identified with where Bobby and I were coming from.
We did not want too many changes too quick as far as the type of music, type of menu.
Soybeans, fuck that.
You know, all kinds of what you might think of as silly arguments about what food's gonna be served and what isn't.
And then on the other hand, I guess 60% of the people on the staff who
came more or less from the university.
And a lot of it was about how much responsibility you had to that activity.

I mean, that was a big conflict with me, because there were several of the people who wanted to have a major voice in how the split rail was run, but they did not spend that much time on staff out there.
They also had other jobs or other things going as far as student life goes.
And we had problems about that.
Big problems.
All of that got intensified to the point where we had a major break.
They threw us out.
Bobby and I went off and spent a couple days thinking about what are we gonna do or what should we do and how do we do it?
And we finally decided that we had to take it back over.
We were legally responsible.
and financially responsible as far as the debts.
And all of it, what was going on was a learning process, too, by the way.
I mean, we didn't know, a lot of us didn't know shit from China about how you handle all the different taxing agencies and how you keep these records.
A lot of dispute going on about whether we were making a profit.
We weren't close to making a profit because we, you've got to, if you know much about business, you're the business one, you know,
Most businesses have regular accounts that you systematically pay into so that when the time comes, you've got to pay the tax man or pay this so that you've got the money there.
And that ain't no profit.
That's a liability, I think, as far as bookkeeping goes.
But it ain't money to be spent.
Don't mess with it.
But we had those kind of arguments.
And we figured that, plus we figured, well, we thought that it would go down financially.
and that it would also go down as far as its role in the community.
Most of the people that came to Split Rail identified with where we were coming from as far as what they wanted as far as music and venue.
Most of the other group, the predominant group in our structure, were for more changes, more changes rapidly.
All of us were for changes.
All of us wanted a chance to form Abbott.
It's a question of how fast.
There we go.
We had a major fight.
We got the police to finally throw them out.

The alternative to that was to throw them out physically, which we could have done because, as I say, most of the split rail clientele identified where we were coming from, most of the working people, the bikers and the laborers and a little bit of everyone.
We didn't want to do it.
We weren't willing to do it.
It would have been bloody because they didn't like where a lot of them were coming from.
We had a number of gay people on staff.
It could have been real shitty.
So we decided to use police and did, which we were severely instilled to this day or severely criticized for using to oust them because we were the legal proprietors.
And then picket lines after that, and it went on and on.
Sadly, very sadly, it caused a major split in the Austin left at that time.
Of course, the Austin left was already having severe problems with sectarianism and sexism and a lot of other things.
But a lot of friendships were split up and heavy-duty criticism back and forth, some of which still exist today.
And that was, I don't know, seven, eight, nine years ago.
Oh, and it makes me very sad.
And I don't think either side was right or wrong in any absolute sense.
It was like all tough problems.
It was a mixed kettle of fish.
You want to go on, or?
Yeah, I'm fine.
If I'm not boring you out or not running out of time.
What were the goals?
Communes?
And were you a member?
And why the whole concept of communism?
You discussed that earlier a little bit.
Yeah.
In addition to the split rail, I don't know what you're talking about as far as what is a commune.
Okay, define commune.
Yeah, the split rail was a community.
I mean, we established a community there that was going, a group that was going to identify and operate the split rail.
So in one sense, that was kind of a commune thing.
The only other two things I was involved with that I remember right now
One of them was Satva.
Don't ask me to spell that.
I think it's a Jewish word or a Middle Eastern word.
It was the first vegetarian restaurant, I guess, in Austin, which we did at the University of Methodist Church, and it was done by a group of activists.
I got into it after it was already functioning.
The University of Methodist Church had a student union, and they had kitchen facilities, big dining room facilities, and you could seat 200 or 300 people.
cafeteria-type line, and they set up this communal restaurant operation.
At one point, I went and worked there.
It was the first time I'd worked at a restaurant in 20 years, although I did back in law school a long time ago.
They, there, we, I don't know, I guess there must have been 15 or 20 of us that were on staff, and I guess two-thirds of them were women.
And
And I guess there were probably six or eight key activists, you know, what traditions would call leaders.

But I didn't think of it that way, and they didn't either, because the one thing the New Left really got clear on is you've got to be very careful about when you start bestowing the leadership label on somebody.
You're going to screw some people up in a hurry if you're not careful.
At any rate, there were six or eight key people, and probably two-thirds of them were winning.
And I thought it
ran real well.
The jobs were rotated.
In other words, you didn't get stuck.
Two days a week, you might be the dishwasher.
One day a week, you might be the chief cook.
All the jobs were rotated, except they did a good job, I thought, of keeping tight control on that bank account.
They had two or three people that took care of the money and the buying.

regular meetings to discuss anything anybody want to discuss whether it was what's going on in the big society how can we relate to it we want to have programs here which we did occasionally we had speakers demonstrations started out of that place we have to organize the bus drivers union here originally the bus drive a bus was hijacked one time and the people that did that that work hijacked i mean they took over a bus and
took it away and it among other things helped pressure the bus company into recognizing the union.
There were some people who were part of that group that organized that little effort and it worked well.
We had art things, movies, theater, plus every day we fed everybody.
And people didn't go away hungry.
I mean, you came to town and it broke.
You could always get beans and rice.
I didn't like the cooking because I'm not a vegetarian.
Most of that stuff is very bland.
You've got to work like crazy to get it very spicy.
They did a good job, and it lasted for a good while.
In fact, it did so well, and I guess I wasn't close enough to the people to understand all the dynamics of this,
Maybe it was because of the tension inside the women's movement at the time, but then some of the women decided if what they really wanted to do was open up another place.
This was called Delta Diner, and it started off as an all-women's group, four or five.
And then I think they finally had a couple of men that worked there.
And they were some of the most talented men
Two of the women, I think, used to be on the Austin newspaper.
They were writers, some singers, dancers.
They had some great songs.
They did some wild theater over there.
They had a place even more in the student neighborhood, and there were a lot more students that we didn't reach at the other place.
But there was a good fraternal relationship between the Delta Banner and Sotlo.
So that's another operating commune operation I was part of.
But as far as what most people, or good many people think of as a commune is when you live together, sleep together in the same house.
For several years, we had a house on 31st and a half street off of Waterloo, right out north of the university.
Owned by Bobby Nelson.
and owned in the sense of most people in the capital society.
In other words, she had mortgage payments, made payments every month, didn't own very much equity.
But she'd had enough credit after she got out of law school, as most young lawyers do, where you could buy something and say you'd pay it off.
So she was on the house.
And she and I were lovers and friends and political comrades.
And...
And it was a, at the time we started, it was a three-bedroom house, had a great big living room, dining room, big high ceilings, a fairly large kitchen, and had a garage out back.
There were two other people that lived there.
That grew, and then Bobby's daughter, who had been maybe with her mother out here a little time, called Lockhart, a very small girl at that time, she came in.
Bobby and I agreed, and she came back and lived with us.
There was Bobby and I and Karen, the little girl, and then Diana and Alice Embry, and then it grew, and grew very much.
Diana had a daughter, Chrissy.
They lived in the front room.
You know Ronnie Duggar, who started the Texas Observer?
Well, at any rate, Ronnie's got a son called Gary Duggar.
Gary and Diana used to be friends and lovers.
Gary lived there for a while.
And then there were a couple, John Muir and Diana, I mean, Alice Embry, who lived in the back bedroom.
It grew, and we were all very active politically in the events that were going on.
always something wrong.
At a big dinner table that I made out of a sheet of pie, we had four by eight.
We could seat 12 to 20 people at that table.
And there were several of us that were good cooks.
And we had lots of organizational meetings and fun times there.
There again, we rotated jobs as far as basic responsibility.
We didn't cook every night, but it was all worked out by the common consensus.
Naturally, it never does work perfectly, and the men are going to fuck up more than the women, and
usually.
But a lot of things got worked out and it was a pretty good situation.
The house grew.
We opened up the attic finally and put in a bedroom and a bath up there and we opened up the garage, put in an apartment by our bedroom with a loft in the garage and we had some more people.
I think at one time we had about ten
10 people, all activists, all political, none sectarian, none liberal Democrats, but all either radicals or revolutionaries.
They're highly active.
Learned a lot.
A lot of that household on the split rail issue, it split, which is one of the things that makes me sad because Alice Emory and John Muir, two people that I dearly love,
ended up with contrary views to mine and Bob's about what should be done on the split ramp.
Some of that's been healed over, but not very much.
But we did, you know, we worked hard at being open and honest.
I mean, anybody could call a meeting.
Anybody could speak up.
If somebody was talking too much like I am, then somebody else would.
You shook a little shit tonight.
Any particular questions?
Strong points.
Really to help increase the pressure on them.
Decision makers to stop the war in Southeast Asia were the May Day demonstrations in the early 1970s.

I don't know whether y'all are familiar with them or not, but there were massive demonstrations in Washington, D.C. And there were more people arrested during that period of time than ever before in the history of the United States.
I think about 14,000 people arrested in a three-day period.
We had a sizable group from Austin that went to that.
We did a lot of intensive work before we went.
And it was called the Armadillo Mayday Tribe.
And a lot of that grew out of that Sotva Delta Diner community.
People had got to know each other and the split rail.
A bunch of the folks had got to meet each other there.
And we had our own literature.
We had our own logos, shirts, t-shirts, all of that.
We were well organized.
After we got there, it turned out we were one of the three or four best organized groups on the scene from out of town.
And, of course, it was a heavy-duty demonstration, lots of brutality by the police, swinging sticks.
About that long, they were like axe handles.
They weren't like night sticks.
About like a baseball bat, not quite as big around as a baseball bat, but they didn't give.
And the fuckers were riding around in these motorsports.
bikes or on a horse, reach over and knock the shit out of you and those things.
And you had to be organized to take care of yourself and your friends.
And we were organized in what we thought was a very good way.
We had what we called affinity groups.
Each group, nationally, assignments were made after we got up there, consensus agreement.

Assignments were made, each group would have a certain target, like you're going to be at Washington Square, or you're going to take this bridge, or you're going to be part of the group that does this, as far as the geographic area.
And then when it comes to the tactics, it generally fell into two categories.
Those groups of people who are like the Quakers, who are nonviolent pacifists, are not going to
Some of them are going to break the law, but they're going to do it in a certain way, like just sit down and not move and get busted.
But they're not going to turn over a car or shut down an intersection or close down a bridge.
They're not going to.
And then there are groups of folks who are going to do a variety of things.
And the only limits we had were that thou shalt not kill or maim, in other words,
draw the line, it physically hurt him.
Although we recognize that as far as self-defense goes, that's another ball of wax.
You get the shit beat out of you, you do whatever you need to do to change that.
If you're not a fool, in my view, I'm not going to stand to get beat if I can help you.
Inside the group that went from Austin, we had those two same strains.

So we had it worked out where certain areas within our big area were and targets were assigned to the group that was going to act a certain way and then the ones that were going to do the other things that might be more risky legally and physically or in the other areas where they wouldn't as much as possible cause pain to the ones who
didn't believe that was.
And what we did, and it worked out well, because you had to worry about undercover agents.
I mean, they did have a lot of informers and some provocateurs.
There's a woman here locally that now we know, we didn't know at the time, was a police agent, a provocateur.
And she was part of that progressive labor group I was talking about, that sectarian malice.
She's a cop.
She's a...
She's the second in command of Westinghouse Security out here.
We go to some of the same music concerts.
At any rate, to combat all of that, well, you worry about the agents, and we had to have what we call affinity groups.
Three, four, five people would get together that knew each other.
And you have what the convictions were and their background, and it cuts down heavily on the possibilities you're going to be infiltrating.
And we had a number of people, affinity groups.
That worked well.
We had a number of people arrested.
It was a three-day activity up there and different targets each day.
I was arrested on the third day.
I went up ahead of, I was talking about advance work.
I went to Mayday, Washington, two weeks in advance to help do some of the advance work as far as...
targets and logistics and all of that shit.

And I also had the responsibility after we got there to, after the demonstration, to try to locate people and see who was in the hospital, who was avoiding the cops, who was busting, trying to get lawyers, all those things.
So it was my responsibility not to get busted the first two days, but
did participate and was arrested on the third day in the steps of the House of Representatives.
And that night, and what's funny, I get a big kick out of it.
That night, they put us in different stadiums and sports arenas.
And they had me, along with several thousand others, in this basketball, I don't even know what it is, basketball arena.
And they wouldn't let us down on the floor, and it was very crowded up where we were, and we were trying to get down there so we could sleep at night.
Finally, some of us jumped the rail and had a confrontation.
I got hit with one of those trucking clubs about like that.
I didn't hurt.
I thought I'd broken my arm.
They sent me to the doctor.
At any rate, I stayed in jail there for 36 hours.
Got out, and we finished up that demonstration, came back to Austin.
And if you follow a legal redress, after that, major lawsuits were filed by the left and by the National Mobilization, by the ACLU, on our behalf.
Different people, different categories, depending on when they were arrested and how.
Ten years later, or no, I guess it was about ten years, eight or ten years later, I got $2,000 because we won.
Nixon, and who was that, Haldeman, those assholes,
Some of the guys on the Supreme Court.
Anyway, we won that lawsuit, and that $2,000 was what we used, Bobby and I, as part of the money to start up Emma Jo's, which was our last club, which is named after Joe Hill and Emma Goldman.
If you know your history, then you know Joe Hill was a poet and a songwriter and a union organizer, a wobbly, and Emma Goldman was a revolutionary intellectual and a great woman.
two of our favorite people.
And so $2,000 of Nixon's fucking money went into starting the Emma Jones.
But that was a major demonstration.
Then we came back home, and it was during that period of time when they were getting ready to dedicate the LBJ library, and fucking Nixon was coming down here.
So we got organized, and we had major demonstrations.
Of course, they, and they had,
the Rockefellers and the Rothschilds and the whole entourage of big, rich shits who were murdering people.
They had ropes to keep us half a mile away if they could, and we had major plans and efforts made to try to put pressure on them.
And again, allow people to do what they wanted to do and were willing to do, those people who wanted to get arrested or that.
What's kind of interesting on a personal level was the day before that, of course, we were open in all of our activities.
You could come to our meetings.
The cops came.
The head of the Red Squad was Bert Gerding, who is the chief officer out at Weston House.
But he was the head of the Red Squad, the one who was charging political activities.
He'd come to our meetings.
The media would.
So they knew generally what was planned.
Of course, they couldn't break into those affinity groups

who would make their own little decisions about what they were going to do the day before the massive demonstration when Nixon was going to be here and Lady Bird and all of them would sit up there and shoot the shit at each other we had our last pre-planning meeting over in East Woods Park which is very close to the LBJ library beautiful place very dense woods and we got over there and there's the goddamn Texas Rangers so if we'd run into them before some other demonstration but usually they're
They were there just for the DPS, and sometimes the soldiers just try to intimidate you.
Of course, that's what they were doing that day, too.
But that day, what they were doing, they were serving papers.
And me and, I think, seven or eight others all got served by the Rangers with papers trying to enjoin us.
from doing anything illegal.
Well, if you know your law, you're not supposed to do anything illegal anyway, and so really the injunction's full of shit.
Except it makes it easier for them to throw you in jail if they don't like something you're doing, and then they can argue later about it on a different basis than if they didn't have the injunction.
